{"id":694,"date":"2021-04-11T16:33:02","date_gmt":"2021-04-11T16:33:02","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/programming.sdarobotics.org\/?page_id=694"},"modified":"2024-09-02T19:28:17","modified_gmt":"2024-09-02T19:28:17","slug":"wiring-the-robot","status":"publish","type":"page","link":"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wiring-the-robot\/","title":{"rendered":"Wiring the robot"},"content":{"rendered":"\n<p>The first thing we need to do is provide power for the robot. For this you will need some kind of battery. We need to create the wiring cable which will connect the battery to both the&nbsp;<strong>Arduino\/Raspberry Pi<\/strong>&nbsp;and the&nbsp;<strong>Motor Controller<\/strong>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>I am using a two cell NiMh battery with a&nbsp;<strong>Tamiya Big Style <\/strong>connector and I have created a wire cable which plugs into the battery\u2019s connector and then splits to provide power to both the Raspberry Pi and Motor Controller. The cable I created looks like this:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><a href=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/PowerConnector.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/PowerConnector.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-698\" width=\"398\" height=\"325\" srcset=\"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/PowerConnector.jpg 1024w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/PowerConnector-300x246.jpg 300w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/PowerConnector-768x629.jpg 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 398px) 100vw, 398px\" \/><\/a><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>And when it is wired to the robot it looks like:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><a href=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/PowerConnection.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/PowerConnection.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-703\" width=\"577\" height=\"467\" srcset=\"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/PowerConnection.jpg 1024w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/PowerConnection-300x243.jpg 300w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/PowerConnection-768x623.jpg 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 577px) 100vw, 577px\" \/><\/a><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Pay very careful attention the the order of the black and red wires for both the connection to the Arduino Board and the Motor Controller. <strong>Connecting these in the wrong order will lead to a very bad result.<\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Next, connect the power to the left and right motors as shown:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><a href=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/MotorPower-anotated.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/MotorPower-anotated.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-708\" width=\"600\" height=\"447\" srcset=\"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/MotorPower-anotated.jpg 1024w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/MotorPower-anotated-300x224.jpg 300w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/MotorPower-anotated-768x574.jpg 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\" \/><\/a><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Next use a four conductor jumper wire to connect pins <strong>4<\/strong>, <strong>5<\/strong>, <strong>6<\/strong>, and <strong>7<\/strong> of the <strong>Arduino <\/strong>to the <strong>Motor Controller<\/strong>. You don&#8217;t need to use the same color wires, but the connections should be made in the order shown below<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><a href=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/ArduinoToMotorController-Anotated.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/ArduinoToMotorController-Anotated-1024x797.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-712\" width=\"587\" height=\"456\" srcset=\"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/ArduinoToMotorController-Anotated-1024x797.jpg 1024w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/ArduinoToMotorController-Anotated-300x234.jpg 300w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/ArduinoToMotorController-Anotated-768x598.jpg 768w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/ArduinoToMotorController-Anotated.jpg 1184w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 587px) 100vw, 587px\" \/><\/a><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Now attach a four conductor jumper wire to the left wheel encoder as shown below. Make a note of which color wire represents each signal type, <strong>Signal A<\/strong>, <strong>Signal B<\/strong>, <strong>5v<\/strong>, and <strong>Ground<\/strong>:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><a href=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/LeftEncoder-anotated-1.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/LeftEncoder-anotated-1-1024x717.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-717\" width=\"595\" height=\"416\" srcset=\"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/LeftEncoder-anotated-1-1024x717.jpg 1024w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/LeftEncoder-anotated-1-300x210.jpg 300w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/LeftEncoder-anotated-1-768x538.jpg 768w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/LeftEncoder-anotated-1.jpg 1267w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 595px) 100vw, 595px\" \/><\/a><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Then attach the other end of the four conductor jumper to analog pins <strong>0<\/strong> and <strong>1<\/strong> of the <strong>Arduino<\/strong>. Take care to match up the pins with the signals as shown below:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><a href=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/LeftEncToArduino-anotated.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/LeftEncToArduino-anotated-1024x641.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-721\" width=\"607\" height=\"379\" srcset=\"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/LeftEncToArduino-anotated-1024x641.jpg 1024w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/LeftEncToArduino-anotated-300x188.jpg 300w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/LeftEncToArduino-anotated-768x481.jpg 768w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/LeftEncToArduino-anotated.jpg 1267w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 607px) 100vw, 607px\" \/><\/a><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Now repeat the process for the right encoder. Attach a four conductor cable to the encoder as shown below:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><a href=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/RightEncoder-Anotated.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/RightEncoder-Anotated-1024x651.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-726\" width=\"602\" height=\"382\" srcset=\"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/RightEncoder-Anotated-1024x651.jpg 1024w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/RightEncoder-Anotated-300x191.jpg 300w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/RightEncoder-Anotated-768x489.jpg 768w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/RightEncoder-Anotated.jpg 1267w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 602px) 100vw, 602px\" \/><\/a><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Then attach the other end to the Arduino analog pins 2 and 3:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><a href=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/RightEncToArduino-anotated-1.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/RightEncToArduino-anotated-1.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-732\" width=\"598\" height=\"440\" srcset=\"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/RightEncToArduino-anotated-1.jpg 1024w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/RightEncToArduino-anotated-1-300x221.jpg 300w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/RightEncToArduino-anotated-1-768x566.jpg 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 598px) 100vw, 598px\" \/><\/a><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Now attach 2 three conductor jumpers to the two <strong>IR Sensors<\/strong> as shown below:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><a href=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/IrSensorConnection-anotated-1.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1024\" height=\"552\" src=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/IrSensorConnection-anotated-1-1024x552.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-740\" srcset=\"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/IrSensorConnection-anotated-1-1024x552.jpg 1024w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/IrSensorConnection-anotated-1-300x162.jpg 300w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/IrSensorConnection-anotated-1-768x414.jpg 768w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/IrSensorConnection-anotated-1-1536x828.jpg 1536w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/IrSensorConnection-anotated-1.jpg 1622w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><\/a><figcaption>binary comment<\/figcaption><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Then connect the other end of the right <strong>IR sensor<\/strong> to pin <strong>11<\/strong> of the <strong>Arduino <\/strong>and the left <strong>IR Sensor<\/strong> to pin <strong>10<\/strong> of the <strong>Arduino <\/strong>as shown below:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><a href=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/IRsensorToArduino-anotated.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/IRsensorToArduino-anotated-1024x804.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-738\" width=\"590\" height=\"463\" srcset=\"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/IRsensorToArduino-anotated-1024x804.jpg 1024w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/IRsensorToArduino-anotated-300x235.jpg 300w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/IRsensorToArduino-anotated-768x603.jpg 768w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/IRsensorToArduino-anotated.jpg 1305w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\" \/><\/a><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Your robot is now wired.<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>The first thing we need to do is provide power for the robot. For this you will need some kind of battery. We need to create the wiring cable which will connect the battery to both the&nbsp;Arduino\/Raspberry Pi&nbsp;and the&nbsp;Motor Controller. I am using a two cell NiMh battery with a&nbsp;Tamiya Big Style connector and I&hellip;&nbsp;<a href=\"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wiring-the-robot\/\" class=\"\" rel=\"bookmark\">Read More &raquo;<span class=\"screen-reader-text\">Wiring the robot<\/span><\/a><\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":2,"featured_media":0,"parent":0,"menu_order":0,"comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"open","template":"","meta":{"neve_meta_sidebar":"","neve_meta_container":"","neve_meta_enable_content_width":"","neve_meta_content_width":0,"neve_meta_title_alignment":"","neve_meta_author_avatar":"","neve_post_elements_order":"","neve_meta_disable_header":"","neve_meta_disable_footer":"","neve_meta_disable_title":""},"_links":{"self":[{"href":"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/pages\/694"}],"collection":[{"href":"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/pages"}],"about":[{"href":"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/types\/page"}],"author":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/users\/2"}],"replies":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/comments?post=694"}],"version-history":[{"count":22,"href":"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/pages\/694\/revisions"}],"predecessor-version":[{"id":3150,"href":"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/pages\/694\/revisions\/3150"}],"wp:attachment":[{"href":"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/media?p